## 1. The `Person` Class

```cpp
Person::Person(string name, string id) : name(name), id(id) {}
Person::~Person() {}
```

`Person` is the **base class** — the parent from which `Student` and `Teacher` both inherit. The constructor takes two parameters: `name` and `id`. The `: name(name), id(id)` part is called an **initializer list**. Instead of writing `this->name = name` inside the body, C++ lets you initialize member variables directly before the constructor body runs. This is considered better practice because it is slightly more efficient, especially for non-primitive types like `string`.

The destructor `~Person()` is defined but has an empty body. It is declared `virtual` in the header file (you can infer this because subclasses override `display()`). Having a virtual destructor is critically important: if you delete a `Student*` pointer that is stored as a `Person*`, the virtual destructor ensures the correct destructor chain is called all the way down. Without this, you would get a **memory leak** or **undefined behavior**.

**Viva Question:** *Why is a virtual destructor important in inheritance?*
Because when you delete a derived class object through a base class pointer, C++ needs to know which destructor to call. Without `virtual`, only the base destructor runs, potentially skipping cleanup in the derived class.

