## 5. The `AuthSystem` Class

```cpp
AuthSystem::AuthSystem() {
    adminCredentials["admin"] = "admin123";
}
```

The constructor initializes a `map<string, string>` with a hardcoded admin username and password. A `map` is a C++ associative container that stores key-value pairs sorted by key. Here, username maps to password.

```cpp
bool AuthSystem::authenticateAdmin(const string& username, const string& password) const {
    auto it = adminCredentials.find(username);
    if (it == adminCredentials.end() || it->second != password)
        throw AttendanceException<string>("Invalid admin credentials!", username);
    return true;
}
```

`find()` returns an iterator to the found element, or `end()` if not found. `it->second` accesses the value (password) of the found key-value pair. If either the username does not exist or the password does not match, an exception is thrown. This is a secure pattern — you don't reveal *which* part was wrong (username or password), making it harder for attackers to probe the system.

**Viva Question:** *Why is it->second used instead of it->first?*
In a `std::map`, each element is a `std::pair<Key, Value>`. `first` is the key (username), and `second` is the value (password). So `it->second` gives us the stored password.

```cpp
void AuthSystem::addStudentCredential(const string& id, const string& password) {
    studentCredentials[id] = password;
}
```

This uses the map's subscript operator `[]` which either inserts a new key-value pair or overwrites an existing one. This means calling this function twice with the same ID simply updates the password.

