## 7. The `saveToHTML()` Method

This is a large method that generates a complete, self-contained HTML file. Rather than using a templating library, it writes HTML directly using `ofstream`. It is structured as follows:

The `<head>` section includes CSS custom properties (variables like `--blue`, `--green`) that define a dark-themed color palette. The `--bg`, `--card`, `--border` variables control background layers. Google Fonts (Syne for headings, DM Sans for body text) are loaded via a CDN link.

The layout uses **CSS Grid** with a sidebar and main area. The sidebar shows navigation links and a summary. The main area has a search input, four statistics cards (total students, teachers, eligible, not eligible), a detailed student table, and a report table.

The student table generates one `<tr>` per student with inline data attributes (`data-name`, `data-id`, `data-dept`) so that the JavaScript search filter can work without a server. A progress bar is drawn using a `<div>` with `width` set to the attendance percentage.

At the bottom, a small `<script>` block implements `filterStudents()`, which reads the search input and hides rows that do not match the query — a simple and effective client-side search.

**Viva Question:** *Why write HTML from C++ rather than use a template engine?*
This is a pure C++ project with no external libraries other than the standard library. Generating HTML directly gives full control without dependencies. For a larger project, a proper template engine would be preferred.

